anings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mauléon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Basque: habitational name from a place called Mauléon-Licharre in French, Maule-Lextarre in Basque, the capital of the Soule province in the French part of the Basque Country. This surname is much more common in Spain, where it is also spelled in a Castilianized form <b>Mauleón</b>, than in France, where it is spelled <b>Mauléon</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Savary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Fabien, Jacques, Normand, Philippe.","French: from the Old French personal name <i>Savari</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Sabaricus</i>, <i>Savaricus</i>, composed of the elements <i>saba</i>, of uncertain meaning, + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’.","English: variant of   Savory  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Savory","meanings":["English (Norfolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Savaric</i>, Old French <i>Savari</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Sabaricus</i>, <i>Savaricus</i>, itself from a stem of uncertain origin + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’."]}]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Chevalier Savary Ier de Mauléon was born in 1181, in Mauléon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, his father, Raoul, III de Mauléon, was 32 and his mother, Alix CHABOT-VOUVENT, was 27. He married Belle-Assez de POUZAUGES in 1200. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters. He died on 29 July 1233, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1181–29 July 1233":"1181–29. juuli 1233","1181–1233":"1181–1233","1175–1227":"1175–1227","1204–1230":"1204–1230","1204–Female":"1204–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1150–1202":"1150–1202","1155–1215":"1155–1215","29 July 1233":"29. juuli 1233","ABT 1202":"umbes 1202","1230":"1230","1175":"1175","ABT 1204":"umbes 1204","ABT 1215":"umbes 1215","ABT 1227":"umbes 1227","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","ABT 1230":"umbes 1230","1202":"1202","ABT 1210":"umbes 1210","1200":"1200","1233":"1233","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","Mauléon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Mauléon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Lusignan,86139,Vienne,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Lusignan, Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa","Mauléon,79079,Deux-Sèvres,Nouvelle-Aquitaine,FRANCE,":"Mauléon, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1181–2